ohn Mandeville, Mandeville’s Travels; Geoffrey Chaucer, Troilus and Criseyde; and Other Items San Marino, CA, Huntington Library MS HM 114 -- tMediation: The Book of Margery Kempe London, British Library MS Additional 61823 -- tPerformance: N-Town Plays London, British Library MS Cotton Vespasian D.viii -- tGLOSSARY -- tPRIMARY WORKS CITED -- tSUGGESTIONS FOR FURTHER R EADING -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Medieval English Manuscripts and Literary Forms, Jessica Brantley offers an innovative introduction to manuscript culture that uses the artifacts themselves to open some of the most vital theoretical questions in medieval literary studies. With nearly 200 illustrations, many of them in color, the book offers both a broad survey of the physical forms and cultural histories of manuscripts and a dozen case studies of particularly significant literary witnesses, including the Beowulf manuscript, the St. Albans Psalter, the Ellesmere manuscript of the Canterbury Tales, and The Book of Margery Kempe. Practical discussions of parchment, scripts, decoration, illustration, and bindings mix with consideration of such conceptual categories as ownership, authorship, language, miscellaneity, geography, writing, editing, mediation, illustration, and performance—as well as of the status of the literary itself.Each case study includes an essay orienting the reader to particularly productive categories of analysis and a selected bibliography for further research. Because a high-quality digital surrogate exists for each of the selected manuscripts, fully and freely available online, readers can gain access to the artifacts in their entirety, enabling further individual exploration and facilitating the book’s classroom use. Medieval English Manuscripts and Literary Forms aims to inspire a broad group of readers with some of the excitement of literary manuscript studies in the twenty-first century. The interpretative frameworks surrounding each object will assist everyone in thinking through the implications of manuscript culture more generally, not only for the deeper study of the literature of the Middle Ages, but also for a better understanding of book cultures of any era, including our own.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aBookszEnglandxHistoryy400-1450. 0aEnglish literatureyMiddle English, 1100-1500xCriticism, Textual. 0aEnglish literatureyMiddle English, 1100-1500xManuscripts. 0aEnglish literatureyOld English, ca. 450-1100xCriticism, Textual. 0aEnglish literatureyOld English, ca. 450-1100xManuscripts. 0aManuscripts, English (Middle). 0aManuscripts, MedievalzEngland. 4aLit Crit-Medieval Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aBeowulf.  aBook of Margery Kempe.  aCanterbury Tales.  aEngland.  acase study.  acodex.  adecoration.  ahandbook.  ahistory of the book.  ailluminated manuscript.  aillumination.  aillustration.  aintroduction.  aliterary form.  amanuscript.  amarginalia.  amedia studies.  amedieval literature.  apaleography.  aparchment.  aphilology.  ascribe.  ascript.  asurvey.  ateaching.  atoolkit.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2022 Englishz978311099375208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural, Area Studies 2022z9783110993738oZDB-23-DKU08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076767440uhttps://doi.org/10.9